         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">27/1/74. ¶  ¶ Since I last wrote to you, dear Mr Bentham, ¶ M to G. Bentham, 1 January 1874. M was granted a free railway pass toAlbury, NSW; see M to J. Francis, 24 December 1873 (in this edition as ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">74.01.27</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, ff. 137-8.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">27/1/74.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Since I last wrote to you, dear Mr Bentham,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        </seg>M to G. Bentham, 1 January 1874. M was granted a free railway pass to<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Albury, NSW; see M to J. Francis, 24 December 1873 (in this edition as 73-12-24a).<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>He did not leave Melbourne until 6 January 1874; see M to R. Ramsay, August 1874<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(in this edition as 74-08-00).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I went out on a short trip to the Australian Alps,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M returned to Melbourne on<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>26 January; see M to J. Francis,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>27 January 1874.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>choosing the Hume-River line for approach,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It is uncertain what current name, if any, represents the stream M calls 'Hume-River';<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>see M to William Branwhite Clarke, 29 January 1874, and notes thereto.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>as in 1854 and 1855 I passed to our Snowy Mountains by the Mitta-Mitta &amp; Snowy River. Having been able to go by different routes proceeding and returning, I have examined a great part of the Hume-district now, and thus gained numerous new localities for Victorian and N.S. Wales species. For Victoria I observed as new: Xanthorrhoea bracteata or an allied species, Apium leptophyllum, Dodonaea triquetra, Andropogon refractus, A. montanus, Aristida calycina, one Cladium, 2 Cyperus species, Carex striata, Westringia, Grevillea acanthifolia or an allied species, 1 Uncina (distinct from the 2 hitherto found) , one Eriocaulon, 1 or 2 Acaciae, — and as new to science I obtained 1 Stackhousia, a Grevillea, an arborescent Bertya rising to 25' hight, one Lemna with almost orbicular fronds and numerous rootlets. These are all from the lower or the subalpine country.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The only new glacier-plant is a<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Ranunculus</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>with entire or only 3-toothed leaves. It is a dwarf perennial with yellow flowers and strigose leaves. it only burst into flowers this month (January), the snow having melted only a few weeks ago, and will cover the plant again before Easter<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>There is an asterisk in the text at this point, indicating where the text of a marginal note was intended to be read. The note, scored through, reads: 'This Ranunculus I have named R. Findlayi, in honor of the Gentleman, who much aided me from his place on the base of the alps in accomplishing my task'.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>See n.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>4.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>so I got no fruit but I obtained fruit of Seseli algens also both sexes of Antennaria uniceps, the female capitula of the latter being much more slender than those of the male plant.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>On the N.S. Wales side of the Hume-river I found the celebrated Eucalyptus Globulus, Atherosperma moschatum, Grevillea Victoriae, Dianella Tasmanica, Casuarina quadrivalvis, Veronica notabilis. Isotoma<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>fluviatilis and several other southern plants. Some of the Eucalypts were puzzling, but hardly any in flower. I noticed an Asplenium, distinct from any known to me; but it may be only of the numerous forms of Asplenium marinum. Of horticultural interest is the tall Corraea<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>ferruginea, which in the sub alpine waters of the Hume-River produces<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">red flowers</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>as magnificent as those of C. speciosa.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It was not to be expected that I should fall in with many absolutely new plants on the alps, having traversed these repeatedly; but I stood sadly in need of a change of air, having lost since months all desire for food and being almost unable to sleep. I feel much invigorated, altho' the heat in the lowlands was excessive, and it was almost beyond my strength to climb the rocky hills, when each rock was daily for many hours as hot as an oven.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Samolus Valerandi (the small flowered variety with membranous leaves), Viola Caleyana, Polygala Japonica are rather common on both sides of the Hume-River, at many spots.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>For Brasenia peltata I have now three new localities, the Hume-River, Mitta Mitta &amp; Upper Murray River. On close examination after my return I find that the Glacier-Ranunculus, mentioned above, is likely a form only of the one, to which you gave so kindly my name.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Ranunculus muelleri</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>was described by Bentham<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(1863-78), vol. 1, <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>p. 13. The final<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>paragraph is written in a darker ink, with which the marginal note (see n.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>3) is also deleted. M instead honoured James Findlay with<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Bertya findlayi</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>'dedicated to a generous man J. Findlay, who with the greatest kindness walked a long way to help in the revealing of this plant'<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(B74.03.01, p. 141).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Always with deep regards your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
